    tool_output=ToolOutput(
        output='Based on the provided excerpts from the S-1 filing, here is a detailed breakdown of what the prospectus says regarding the X platform\'s revenue, monetization strategies, supported accounts, and Monthly Active Users (MAUs):\n\n### 1. Supported Accounts and Monthly Active Users (MAUs)\nThe filing outlines significant scale and growth across the integrated X and Grok platforms, while explicitly defining how these metrics are calculated:\n*   **Current Metrics (as of March 31, 2026):** The platforms have over **1.3 billion supported accounts** active in the last twelve months, including approximately **550 million MAUs**. The platforms generate approximately **350 million daily posts**.\n*   **Growth Trajectory:** This represents an increase from over 1.1 billion supported accounts and approximately 520 million MAUs as of December 31, 2025.\n*   **Grok AI Adoption:** Of the total MAUs, approximately **117 million MAUs** actively used Grok’s AI features as of March 31, 2026.\n*   **Metric Definitions & Methodologies:** \n    *   **Supported Accounts:** Defined as any human, bot, or similar account that logged into X or Grok. The filing notes this number *may include fake, spam, or bot accounts* if they are active.\n    *   **MAUs:** Users who interacted with Grok or X via web or mobile at least once in a 30-day period. Only registered users are included. The company attempts to deduplicate users who access both platforms based on sign-in traffic, though it acknowledges this is an estimate and may not capture all duplication.\n*   **Strategic Priority (Revenue over MAU):** The filing explicitly states that while MAUs estimate user base size and engagement, **the company is focused on revenue and operating margin**. The primary objective is driving sustainable revenue growth and profitability, *rather than* growing or maintaining MAU levels.\n\n### 2. Monetization Strategies and Revenue Streams\nThe company monetizes the X platform through a diversified mix of advertising, consumer subscriptions, enterprise AI, and emerging financial services:\n\n*   **Advertising (Core Channel):** \n    *   X monetizes user activity through high-impact, performance-based advertising inventory (e.g., Promoted Ads, Vertical Video, Takeovers). \n    *   **AI Integration:** Grok is increasingly used to help advertisers with campaign creation, creative optimization, and aligning with trending topics/user intent. \n    *   **New Ad Platform:** In April 2026, the company began rolling out a rebuilt, AI-powered **X Ads Manager** for more precise, dynamic ad delivery and real-time monitoring.\n*   **Consumer Subscriptions:** \n    *   The company is focused on converting free users into paying subscribers via **X Premium/Premium+** and **Grok tiers** (SuperGrok, SuperGrok Heavy, SuperGrok Lite).\n    *   **Subscriber Base:** As of March 31, 2026, there were approximately **6.3 million active paid subscribers** (4.4 million for X Premium/Premium+ and 1.9 million for SuperGrok tiers).\n*   **Enterprise AI & Data Licensing:**\n    *   **Enterprise Deployments:** Tailored deployments of Grok (Grok Business and Grok Enterprise) customized for specific workflows and security needs, sold on license-, consumption-, or outcome-based pricing models.\n    *   **Data Licensing:** Developers and enterprises pay to access, search, and analyze X’s real-time and historical intellectual property/data via APIs.\n*   **The "Everything App" & New Channels:**\n    *   **X Money:** Launched in beta in November 2025, this product aims to expand platform utility by enabling payments, banking, and financial services.\n    *   **X Chat:** Released in November 2025, featuring end-to-end encryption with no connection to ad personalization.\n\n### 3. Revenue Performance (2024 vs. 2025)\nThe MD&A section highlights a shift in the company\'s revenue composition, showing a recovery in advertising and massive growth in AI/subscription revenues:\n*   **2024 Performance:** Total revenue *decreased* by $341 million (11.5%). This was driven by a massive **$595 million drop in advertising revenue** due to the loss of advertising partners on X. However, this was partially offset by a $254 million increase in AI solutions/infrastructure (driven by X subscriptions and data licensing).\n*   **2025 Performance:** Total revenue *increased* by $581 million (22.2%). Advertising revenue rebounded with a **$116 million increase** as ad spend recovered. AI solutions and infrastructure revenue surged by **$465 million**, fueled by a $365 million jump in X/Grok subscription revenue and an $88 million increase in data licensing.\n*   **Seasonality:** Advertising revenues experience seasonality, typically peaking in Q4 (end-of-year spend) and hitting their lowest point in Q1.\n\n### 4. Risks to User Base and Monetization\nThe Risk Factors section outlines several vulnerabilities tied to X\'s user base and revenue models:\n*   **Advertiser Volatility:** Advertisers generally lack long-term commitments to X and may reduce or halt spending for reasons outside the company\'s control.\n*   **User Decline & Content Quality:** If users migrate to other platforms, fail to contribute content, or if the platform is plagued by "problematic or offensive" content, monetizable usage and subscription revenues will decline. This could also cause severe brand and reputational harm.\n*   **Impact on AI Development:** A decline in the volume or quality of user-generated content on X directly threatens the ongoing development of Grok, which relies on X\'s real-time data and human discourse for training and "truth-seeking" contextual awareness.\n*   **Fierce Competition in Fintech:** The planned public launch of the "Money Product" pits the company against large, established financial and tech companies with significantly greater resources and market presence.',
