2026-06-09 16:27:27,413 DEBUG Tool call: submit_final_result({'final_result': '## Distinguishing Starlink Subscriber, Service Line, and Supported Accounts\n\nBased on the SpaceX S-1 filed May 20, 2026, these three metrics are defined in the filing\'s glossary and key business metrics sections as follows:\n\n---\n\n### 1. Service Line (The Fundamental Technical Unit)\n\n**Definition:** "An individual instance of Starlink broadband internet service provisioned under a subscription plan, generally associated with a specific Starlink User Terminal or group of terminals, and billed according to Starlink\'s service plans and terms of service."\n\n**Key characteristics:**\n- It is the atomic unit of Starlink service delivery.\n- It is explicitly **not** equivalent to a unique device, account holder, end user, or physical person.\n- A single individual, household, or business may hold **multiple** Service Lines (e.g., one Residential line and one Roam line = two Service Lines).\n- Conversely, multiple end-users may **share** a single Service Line (e.g., a household).\n- Service Lines exist across **all** customer categories—consumer, enterprise, and government.\n\n---\n\n### 2. Starlink Subscriber (A Commercially Defined Subset of Service Lines)\n\n**Definition:** "A unique Service Line that is directly assigned to a Starlink.com account registered to a person or entity that **does not have a direct, negotiated agreement** with the Starlink sales team."\n\n**Key characteristics:**\n- Calculated as the number of unique Service Lines at the end of the period.\n- **Includes** Personal subscriptions (Residential, Roam) and Business subscriptions (Local Priority, Global Priority).\n- **Explicitly excludes** managed enterprise and government customers with negotiated contracts in aviation, maritime, land mobility, fixed sites, and government entities.\n- **Count:** ~10.3 million as of March 31, 2026 (up from ~5.0 million as of March 31, 2025—a 105% YoY increase).\n\nBecause Starlink Subscribers are defined as a subset of Service Lines, the **total number of Service Lines across all of Starlink (including enterprise/government) is necessarily higher** than the Starlink Subscriber count, though the filing does not disclose the total.\n\n---\n\n### 3. Supported Accounts (An X/Grok Platform Engagement Metric)\n\n**Definition:** "A human, bot, or similar account that logged into the X platform or Grok."\n\n**Key characteristics:**\n- Applies exclusively to the **X platform and Grok AI**—it has no connection to Starlink.\n- **May include fake, spam, or bot accounts** if they are active.\n- **Count:** Over **1.3 billion** supported accounts active in the last twelve months ended March 31, 2026 (up from ~1.1 billion as of December 31, 2025).\n- The filing separately reports ~550 million Monthly Active Users (MAUs) and ~117 million Grok AI MAUs, both of which are subsets of supported accounts.\n- The filing explicitly acknowledges that the company is "focused on revenue and operating margin" rather than growing or maintaining MAU levels.\n\n---\n\n## Comparative Analysis\n\n| Metric | Domain | Count (Q1 2026) | Includes Non-Paying? | Includes Non-Human? |\n|---|---|---|---|---|\n| **Service Line** | Starlink (all segments) | Not fully disclosed (>10.3M) | No—each is a billed service instance | No |\n| **Starlink Subscriber** | Starlink (consumer only) | ~10.3 million | No—each is a paying subscription | No |\n| **Supported Accounts** | X / Grok platform | ~1.3 billion | Yes—vast majority are free users | Yes—bots and spam included |\n\n---\n\n## Which Is Most Analogous to a Revenue-Generating Customer?\n\n**Starlink Subscriber** is the most analogous to a revenue-generating customer. Each Starlink Subscriber represents a unique, actively billed subscription line generating recurring monthly service revenue (and typically an upfront hardware sale). The filing ties this metric directly to consumer revenue, noting that consumer subscribers represented over 60% of Connectivity segment revenue in 2025, and tracks Starlink Subscriber ARPU (Average Revenue Per User) as a key financial metric.\n\nA **Service Line** is the closest conceptual equivalent but is a technical/operational unit rather than a commercial one. Importantly, the Starlink Subscriber metric is *derived from* Service Lines—it is literally defined as a count of a specific subset of them.\n\n**Supported Accounts** are the least analogous to revenue-generating customers. The vast majority of the 1.3 billion supported accounts are free, non-paying users (and potentially bots/spam). Only ~6.3 million active paid subscribers (X Premium/Premium+ and SuperGrok tiers) directly generate subscription revenue on the X platform—a tiny fraction of the total.\n\n---\n\n## Which Has the Highest Count?\n\n**Supported accounts** have by far the highest count at **~1.3 billion**, exceeding Starlink Subscribers (~10.3 million) by roughly two orders of magnitude (approximately 126x).\n\n**Why:** Supported accounts measure any login event on a global social media and AI platform over a twelve-month window, with no quality filter (bots, spam, and duplicate accounts are included). Starlink Subscribers, by contrast, measure only paying broadband subscriptions on a satellite network with finite capacity and hardware requirements, and explicitly exclude the enterprise/government segment. The fundamental difference is between an open, free-to-use digital platform with minimal friction to account creation and a paid hardware-dependent satellite internet service.\n\n---\n\n**Sources:**\n{\n  "sources": [\n    {\n      "url": "https://www.sec.gov/Archives/edgar/data/1181412/000162828026036936/spaceexplorationtechnologi.htm",\n      "name": "SpaceX S-1 Registration Statement (filed May 20, 2026)"\n    }\n  ]\n}'})
